title: bow_(weapon)
body:
A bow is a [[weapon]] that shoots [[arrow (projectile)|]]s. The weapon is used for hunting, sport shooting, and occasionally for war.

Regular bows (covered by this tag) are pulled back manually, which takes more strength than popular belief would tend to attribute to the typical archer character in fiction. However, in later times, a version of the weapon called a [[crossbow]] would arise, which replaces manual pulling of the string with pulling by means of a mechanical device such as a lever or a crank, which allows for more powerful shots and can be used by those with less strength than a regular archer.

title: chaise_longue
body:
A chaise longue (French for "long chair") is an upholstered [[couch|sofa]] in the shape of a chair that is long enough to support the legs.

It is also known as a "chaise lounge" (Primarily North American) due to a misspelling of the name during its introduction in North America.  Given the purpose of the chair was to lounge around on, the misspelled naming has stuck.

The outdoor furniture called [[lounge_chair|sun loungers/lounge chairs]] are also referred to as "chaise lounges" in North America, likely due to the similar shape.

The French now use the term "chaise longue" to refer to any kind of long reclining chair, such as deck chairs and sun loungers, but for tagging purposes this tag is only for the indoor furniture.

title: trading_card
body:
A [b]trading card[/b], also known as [b]collectible card[/b], are [[card]]s that are traditionally included in products such as [[cigarette]]s, [[food]], and [[candy]]. Originally depicting sportpersons, automobiles, and scenery. Though in later era, trading cards usually depict characters from fictional works, typically from movie or television series.

Since the creation of [[Magic: The Gathering]] in 1993, a derivative of trading card known as trading [[card game]] has emerged, which involves using these cards as a game piece. These has since supplanted the traditional trading card market, albeit the non-game trading cards (such as [[soccer|footballer]] cards) were still being produced to this day.

This tag is applicable to the depiction of either trading cards or the trading card games, including the real and fan-made card face. If the cards were shown to be played, the tag [[card game]] is applicable.
other_names: トレーディングカード

title: 1pn58
body:
A [[Soviet]] designed passive [b][[night vision|night]] [[scope]][/b] for a range of Soviet designed [[gun|small arms]] and [[grenade launcher]]s. The name comes from the GRAU index. 1PN is the GRAU index of night vision devices, where PN stands for [i]Nochnoy Pritsel[/i] (Russian: Ночной прицел) meaning night sight. It is also called NSPUM (НСПУМ) or NSPU-1. The scope was introduced into Soviet [[military]] service in the early 1970s and is still used by many of the Soviet Union's successor states, and has been used in numerous armed conflicts around the world.

The 1PN58 gathers light into a refractor which can be protected with an aperture cover. The center of the cover has a circular aperture with dark glass allowing the scope to be used in light conditions that would otherwise saturate the light intensifier. For zeroing the sight the left side of the scope has two perpendicular knobs, of which the elevation knob has a detachable scale. The scope comes with seven different, detachable elevation scales, one for each of the supported weapons. Its magnification power is 3.5×.

Any [[weapon]] fitted with the Soviet-style dovetail mount can technically use this optic. The following weapons can use the 1PN58, such as:
* [[AKM]]
* [[AK-74]]
* AK-100 series 
* [[AS Val]]
* [[Dragunov SVD]] and SVDK
* [[PKM]]
* [[PSL Romak]]
* [[RPG-7]]
* [[RPK-74]] and RPK-74M

title: twister_(submission_hold)
body:
A sideways body bend and neck crank-type [[submission hold]] in [[mixed martial arts]], which involves forcing the head towards the shoulder while controlling the body, hence causing lateral hyperflexion of the cervical spine. 

The technique involves tension in several body parts, and depending on the flexibility of the recipient, can also involve pain in the knees, abdominals and torso. The twister is often confused as being a spine crank since it involves a degree of lateral non-cervical spinal flexion. The main pressure is however on the cervical spine, hence making it a neck crank. It is performed from a back mount single vine ride position, where the top man has one "hook" threaded through the bottom man's legs and secured behind the ankle. The top man then pulls the bottom man's opposite arm behind his own head and grabs hold of his opponent's head, pulling it down to his shoulder. 

It resembles a hold in professional [[wrestling]] called the [I][[Cobra Twist]][/I] (actually, the latter is basically its standing counterpart) though the Twister itself is used in pro wrestling as well, being popularized by former [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] fighter and current [[WWE]] wrestler Matt Riddle, calling his version of the hold as the [I]Bromission[/I].

title: osmanthus_fragrans
body:
[b]Osmanthus fragrans[/b], commonly known as sweet osmanthus, sweet olive, tea olive, fragrant olive, and in Japanese as [i]mokusei[/i], is a species of the [[Osmanthus]] genus of plants native to southeast Asia.

It is an evergreen shrub or small tree, with clusters of small (1 cm), four-lobed flowers ranging in color from white through pale yellow to orange-yellow. In Japan, subspecies with white and orange flowers are distinguished, called "[[silver osmanthus]]" (銀木犀, [i]ginmokusei[/i]) and "[[gold osmanthus]]" (金木犀, [i]kinmokusei[/i]) respectively.

It is widely cultivated, both in and out of its native range, for its strong fragrance. Its flowers are used in jams, desserts, and as an infusion for tea.

title: h&k_xm8
body:
A lightweight [[assault rifle]] system developed from the late 1990s to early 2000s. The [[rifle]] was designed by German small arms manufacturer Heckler & Koch, and shares design and engineering with their [[h&k g36|G36]] rifle.
The XM8 is a selective-fire 5.56×45mm NATO assault rifle, firing from a closed rotary bolt. Its design and functioning is similar to that of the G36, of which it is a derivative.

The materials used to build the XM8 are almost entirely composites, with the notable exception of the cold-hammer-forged steel barrel. Preliminary tests in [[desert]] and arctic conditions have shown the XM8 to be a rugged weapon, though some complaints arose.

While the XM8 fell out of favor with the US military, Heckler & Koch sought to market the rifle globally. In the meantime, the Malaysian Armed Forces expressed interest in using the rifle and by 2007 openly stated its intention to purchase the XM8 rifle. By 2010, the Royal Malaysian Navy special unit PASKAL began using the XM8 along with other Heckler & Koch assault rifles including the [[h&k hk416|HK416]] and G36.

"Wikipedia page":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heckler_%26_Koch_XM8]

The 2022 FIFA World Cup was the 22nd FIFA [[World Cup]], a tournament for the men's [[soccer]] world championship, taking place in [[Qatar]] from 20 November to 18 December 2022. It was the first World Cup to take place in the Middle East, the first to be held in autumn in the northern hemisphere, and the first to not be held in either May, June, or July, known to be extremely hot months in Qatar.

[[Argentina]] won their third World Cup against [[France]] in a 4-2 penalty shootout, after a 3-3 draw in extra time.

Even before the tournament began, it became the focal point of numerous controversies, primarily revolving around allegations of bribery of FIFA officials for the rights to host the tournament, poor treatment of workers (mostly immigrants), and suppression of LGBT rights.

title: f-104_starfighter
body:
The [i]Lockheed[/i] [b]F-104 Starfighter[/b] is a single-engine, supersonic interceptor aircraft originally developed by Lockheed for the United States Air Force (USAF). One of the Century Series of aircraft, it was operated by the air forces of more than a dozen nations (including the [[Japan Air Self-Defense Force]]) from 1958 to 2004.

The F-104 served with the USAF from 1958 until 1969, and continued with Air National Guard units until 1975. The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) flew a small mixed fleet of F-104 types in supersonic flight tests and spaceflight programs until 1994.

USAF F-104Cs saw service during the [[Vietnam War]], and F-104A aircraft were deployed by Pakistan briefly during the Indo-Pakistani wars. Republic of China Air Force (Taiwan) F-104s also engaged the People's Liberation Army Air Force (China) over the disputed island of Quemoy. The operational service of the Starfighter ended with its retirement by the Italian Air Force in May 2004.

title: siamese_fighting_fish
body:
The Siamese fighting fish (Betta splendens), commonly known as the betta, is a freshwater fish native to Southeast Asia.

Although aquarium specimens are widely known for their brilliant colors and large, flowing fins, the natural coloration of B. splendens is generally green, brown and grey, while the fins are short; wild fish exhibit strong colors only when agitated. In captivity, Siamese fighting fish have been selectively bred to display a vibrant array of colors and tail types.

title: siren_head
body:
Siren Head is a hostile cryptid and urban legend created by the artist Trevor Henderson. [b]Siren Head[/b] itself is a 40-foot-tall humanoid creature with a heavily emaciated, near-skeletal frame covered in dried, mummified flesh the color of rusty metal. It's limbs are disproportionately long and thin, with arms as long as it's legs, ending in huge, bony hands. Where it's head and neck would be is a thin pole of flesh with two sirens attached to them [i](hence the name)[/i], and several black wires snaking around it's "neck" and into it's upper shoulders, pressed against it's abdomen. These speakers are the only metal parts of it's body, fused to the neck by tendrils of skin and capable of swiveling around it much like the head of an owl. Some images depict [b]Siren Head's[/b] speakers with toothy, lipless human-like jaws and a long, retractable thin snake-like tongue. [quote]
Trevor Henderson said: though the teeth are only visible on a certain radio frequency.
[/quote]

title: gatchaman
body:
[b]Science Ninja Team Gatchaman[/b] ([i]Kagaku Ninja Tai Gatchaman[/i]) is a 5 member superhero team from the 70s created by Tatsuo Yoshida and originally produced in Japan by [[Tatsunoko Pro]] and later adapted into several English language versions. It is also known by the abbreviated name [i]Gatchaman[/i].

title: sterling_smg
body:
A British 9×19mm Parabellum [[submachine gun]]. It was tested with the British Army in 1944–1945 as a replacement for the [[Sten gun]], but it did not start to replace it until 1953. A successful and reliable design, it remained as standard issue with the British Army until 1994, when it began to be replaced by the [[L85]] [[assault rifle]].

The Sterling utilizes conventional blowback open bolt design. Its bolt has helical grooves cut into the surface to remove dirt and fouling from the inside of the receiver to increase reliability. The weapon is constructed entirely of (stamped) steel and plastic and has a bottom-folding stock. Similar to the its predecessor, the [[magazine (weapon)|magazine]] is inserted sideways.

[b]Oushitsu Kyoushi Heine[/b], also known by its English name [b]The Royal Tutor[/b], is a comedy, historical-inspired manga series by [[Akai Higasa]]. It has an anime adaptation and stage play, as well as an original movie.

The protagonist [[Heine Wittgenstein]], a man often mistaken for a small child, has been summoned to the royal palace of Granzreich by [[viktor von granzreich|the king]] to act as the royal tutor to the four younger princes—[[kai von granzreich|Kai]], [[bruno von granzreich|Bruno]], [[leonhard von granzreich|Leonhard]], and [[licht von granzreich|Licht]]–turning them into capable candidates to the throne. However, he finds his task difficult because of the complicated personalities of his charges, who had managed to cause every tutor they had to quit. The story follows Heine’s journey to offer the princes the education they need most, help them with their issues, and unravel the complicated nature of both the royalty’s life and his own mysterious past.

title: kazuhira_miller
body:
A recurring character in the [[Metal Gear_(series)|]] series, usually providing support, advice, and intel. 

His appearance varies depending on which game he's in, but he'll always be seen with [[blonde hair]] and [[sunglasses]].

In [[Metal Gear 2]] and [[Metal Gear Solid]], he wears a [[tank top]], [[black gloves]], a [[ponytail]], and either a [[whistle around neck|whistle around his neck]] or [[dog tags]]. He's also commonly featured with a [[prosthetic arm]], but it's unknown if he actually got a prosthetic in canon.

In [[Metal Gear Solid: Peace Walker]], he wears a [[yellow ascot]](?), a [[green shirt]] with its [[sleeves rolled up]], a [[wristwatch]], and [[boots]].

In [[Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain]], he becomes a [[double amputee]] after being tortured. He wears a [[beret]], a [[green shirt|green]] [[collared shirt]], a [[red_necktie]], a [[coat]], a [[cane]], a [[vest]], and a [[stubble]]. 

Voiced by Banjo Ginga(MGS1) and [[Sugita Tomokazu]] (PW, MGSV) in Japanese, and by Cam Clarke(MGS1) and Robin Atkin Downes (PW, MGSV) in English.

title: mortar_shell
body:
[b][[Explosive]] [[ammunition]][/b] that is loaded in and fired from [b][[mortar (weapon)|mortar]]s[/b]. It is also commonly referred as mortar round or [[bomb]]. It comes in various calibers. Mortar shells generally comes in two main varieties: fin-stabilized and spin-stabilized.
Lighter (approximately 60 mm) mortar shells could be thrown by hand like [[grenade]]s, but with shorter range due to its weight and higher risk. [spoiler]In fact, few "soldiers during World War II could do that":[https://www.wearethemighty.com/popular/yes-world-war-ii-soldiers-could-throw-mortar-rounds-like-grenades/]. This action is featured on movies like Saving Private Ryan and Hacksaw Ridge.[/spoiler]

Mortars can fire different types of shells. Some of these are:
* [b]High explosive.[/b] This is a normal round which explodes when it hits the ground.
* [b]Smoke round.[/b] This creates thick smoke, it can be various colours. It is fired on enemy positions or in open areas to block visibility, so friendly forces can move without being visible.
* [b]White phosphorus.[/b] This makes a thick [[smoke]] screen to blind and burn the enemy, causing second and third degree burns from the explosion.
* [b][[Illumination]] round.[/b] This is a flare which hangs underneath a parachute. It lights up the [[battlefield]] at night.

"Wikipedia page":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mortar_(weapon)#Ammunition]

title: rickshaw
body:
A two-wheeled vehicle intended to be pulled by a person. The English word is a borrowing from the Japanese [i]jinrikisha[/i], literally "human-powered cart".

Formerly ubiquitous in many Asian cities, the introduction of automobiles and trains caused their gradual disappearance over the course of the 20th century. They retain vintage appeal for many however, and can still be found in some areas of Kyoto and Tokyo.

title: texas_cloverleaf
body:
A spine-targeting [[submission hold]] where the wrestler performing the move stands at the feet of the supine opponent, grabs the opponent's legs, and lifts them up. The wrestler then bends one leg so that the shin is behind the knee of the straight leg and places the ankle of the straight leg in their armpit. With the same arm, they reach around the ankle and through the opening formed by the legs, and lock their hands together. The wrestler then steps over his opponent, turning the opponent over as in a [[scorpion deathlock]] or a [[boston crab]] and proceeds to squat and lean back.

It is also known as just the [i]Cloverleaf[/i], or [i]Texas Cloverhold[/i] in Japan. Famous users include wrestling legend [[Dory Funk Jr]] (who is the innovator of the hold), WCW & [[WWE]] alumnus Dean Malenko, [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] wrestler [[Tanahashi Hiroshi]], WWE wrestler [[Sheamus]], and [[Tokyo Joshi Pro Wrestling]] wrestler [[Itou Maki (wrestler)|]]. The late wrestling legend [[Eddie Guerrero]] has a variation of the Texas Cloverleaf where he performs the maneuver from a standing position, which enabled him to pull the opponent's legs up high enough to where he could add pressure to the hold by sticking one of his knees into the other wrestler's back. Guerrero referred to the move as the [i]Lasso from El Paso[/i], making reference to his hometown of El Paso, Texas.

title: georgy_malenkov
body:
Georgy Maximilianovich Malenkov, a politician of the Soviet Union, was for the short period of time that he was interim leader between Stalin and Khruschev, the most powerful person in the Soviet Union.

After losing power he became the head of a hydroelectric power plant in Ust-Kamenogorsk, Ekibastuz GRES-1 thermal power station, but his name was eventually struck from the communist party register.

In Japan, he was known for his weak presence and was often called ”マなんとかさん (Ma-whatshisname-san)” and people joked that ”the reason the Soviet Union fell was because he had disrupted the 'Bald-Hairy Theory’.”

[[Mana (rune factory)|]], the inconspicuous heroine of [[Rune Factory 2]] is also called 'Ma-whatshername-san', but the origin of this joke for both people is unknown.

title: gakusei_undou
body:
A Japanese term for student activism that is often used to refer to "the Japanese New Left wave":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_New_Left from the 1950s to 70s, its political movements and groups.

Various individual groups, political movements and incidents are associated with this term. For example the "Kakumaru-ha":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japan_Revolutionary_Communist_League_%28Revolutionary_Marxist_Faction%29], the "Chuukaku-ha":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revolutionary_Communist_League,_National_Committee], the post-50s "Zengakuren":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zengakuren], "Zenkyoutou":[https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%85%A8%E5%AD%A6%E5%85%B1%E9%97%98%E4%BC%9A%E8%AD%B0], "Toudai Funsou":[https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%9D%B1%E5%A4%A7%E7%B4%9B%E4%BA%89], etc. When one of those organizations, "the Rengou Sekigun":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Red_Army], caused the "Asama-Sansou incident":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asama-Sans%C5%8D_incident], and members of "the Nihon Sekigun":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_Red_Army] were found to be involved in the "Lod Airport massacre":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lod_Airport_massacre], they lost all support from the public and went into decline, even impacting broader political discussion by rendering it a "private":https://twitter.com/OnTakahashi/status/1341536212280954880 matter.

They are stereotyped as being equipped with construction [[helmet]]s, dust [[mask]]s and [[log|square timber]] (sometimes [[lead pipe|steel pipes]] and [[Molotov cocktail]]s), sticking [[flyer]]s with various [[propaganda]] slogans (for example, "Never allow!!" "Crush the unfair **!!" "We will win this conflict!!" etc.) all over the place, and for separating into numerous groups and infighting. The various portmanteaus using Geba and Aji were created from student activism, and each derive from "gewalt" (German for "violence") and "agitation".

The square timber mentioned earlier are called "geba-bou":[http://dic.pixiv.net/a/%E3%82%B2%E3%83%90%E6%A3%92] (gewalt stick), internal conflict is called "uchi-geba":https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%86%85%E3%82%B2%E3%83%90 (internal gewalt), flyers are "aji-bira":https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E3%82%A2%E3%82%B8%E3%83%93%E3%83%A9 (agitation flyers), and the fonts used for these purposes are called "geba-moji":http://www.pixiv.net/search.php?s_mode=s_tag_full&word=%E3%82%B2%E3%83%90%E6%96%87%E5%AD%97 (gewalt fonts).

h4.See also

title: abyssal_crane_princess
body:
Final Boss of the Winter 2018 Event in [i]Kantai Collection[/i].

Essentially the [[abyssal ship|abyssal]] [[dark persona|counterpart]] of [[Zuikaku (Kancolle)|]], obviously shown by her name (containing the kanji 鶴 "crane" for Zui[b]kaku[/b]) and her appearance in the operation that alludes to her historical final battle. Her hair is upwards referencing "her crew as they salute as the flag is lowered during her sinking":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_aircraft_carrier_Zuikaku#/media/File:Lowering_the_flag_on_Zuikaku.jpg. Also seemingly amalgamated into her being are elements from [[musashi (kancolle)|Musashi]] (sunk in Sibuyan Sea, 10-24-1944) and [[zuihou (kancolle)|Zuihou]] (sunk off Cape Engano, 10-25-1944), evident in the turret on her back and the [[hakama skirt]] that she wears.

Given that the event (and the preceding one) tackles the battle of Leyte Gulf including the encounter off Cape Engano where Zuikaku was sunk, the reference should not come as a surprise.

title: lotus
body:
An aquatic plant belonging to the Nelumbonaceae family of flowering plants. The lotus has prominent blooms (of pink or white hues) rising 8-12 inches above the water, each with a flattened central seed pod structure and fully circular leaves with centrally-attached stems. These features help distinguish it from the [[water lily flower]] (Nymphaea), with which it is often confused.

[i]Nelumbo nucifera[/i] (also known as the Sacred or Indian Lotus) will probably be the plant of interest to Danbooru image taggers, being a divine symbol in Hinduism and Buddhism. It conveys the virtues of purity and non-attachment; it is associated with beauty, elegance, and grace.

title: trypophobia
body:
Trypophobia (蓮コラ, lit. "Lotus collage", or 集合体恐怖症, "fear of aggregate patterns") is a repulsion towards seeing patterns of clusters of holes, such as those found on [[lotus pod]]s and insect nests. People who have trypophobia experience symptoms such as itching and general discomfort upon looking at images with such patterns. 

Use this tag for posts that trigger trypophobia. Common examples are human figures and faces with clusters of shallow holes.

h4. See also

She is quite shy and destroys all the electric devices she touches. When she begins to think about going out of the mountains and moving to the city, her guardian Sagara Yukimasa recommends her to enter a high school in Tokyo and forces his son [[sagara_miyuki|Miyuki]] to serve [[suzuhara_izumiko|Izumiko]] for life. [[sagara_miyuki|Miyuki]] and [[suzuhara_izumiko|Izumiko]] repel each other but their relationship begins to change when a terrifying accident occurs on the school excursion. [quote] 
Living by the sea, protecting the sea, and journeying across the sea... They're the Blue Mermaids!

Because of a shift in tectonic plates around 100 years ago, Japan lost much of its area to submergence. To preserve Japan's territories, coastal cities sprung up, one after the other. Eventually, they became marine cities, and along with the expansion of sea-lanes to connect them, the need arose for a sizable staff to protect the seas.

At the same time, maritime jobs were becoming more popular among women. Hence, the Blue Mermaids, tasked with keeping the seas safe, had become every female student's dream job. title: haast's_eagle
body:
[b]Haast's eagles[/b] ([i]Hieraaetus moorei[/i]) are an [[extinct]] species of [[eagle]] and the largest eagle known to have existed, they once lived in the South Island of New Zealand. Its massive size evolved to cope with the increasing size of its prey, the flightless [[moa (animal)|]]. 

Haast's eagle became extinct after the moa were hunted to extinction by the first Māori.

Knowledge of Haast's eagle survives in Māori legend in the form of the "poukai".

title: tasmanian_devil
body:
The [b]Tasmanian devil[/b] ([i]Sarcophilus harrisii[/i]) is a carnivorous marsupial native to the [[Australia]]n island state of Tasmania with a small population in the Australian mainland. 

Listed as endangered since 2008, it is known for its distinctive black [[fur]] and loud screeching sound, becoming a symbol of Tasmania and Australian wildlife.

title: thylacine
body:
The [b]thylacines[/b] ([i]Thylacinus cynocephalus[/i], also called [b]Tasmanian tigers[/b]) are an extinct species of marsupials once native to Tasmania, Papua, and the Australian mainland. Due to convergent evolution on account of their unique habitat conditions, they developed tiger-like features like stripes and canid skulls. 

The "tiger" tag should not be applied when tagging due to the thylacine being technically [b]a mammal[/b].

Known in Japanese as [i]Fukuro-ookami[/i] (袋狼).

title: passenger_pigeon
body:
The [b]passenger pigeons[/b] ([i]Ectopistes migratorius[/i]) is an extinct species of [[pigeon]]s that were once endemic to North America, named so for their migratory nature (French: [i]passager[/i], meaning "to pass by"). 

Known in Japanese as [i]Ryokoubato[/i] (旅行鳩).
